<br>
Now... is a level 40 druid and a level 10 killing a level 39 hill giant trivial work? Nope.. the level 10 might just be grouped to learn a language point, chat convenience, who knows... <br>
<br>
If that's not a bug, it certainly isn't a feature that makes sense. All it does is make folks paranoid about disbanding first before doing the finishing kill.<br>
<br>
The other one I mentioned was going out of range... take my group yesterday. 2 druids, myself.  We were trying to do the kromrif military leggings quest.  Bit of a bad time resulted in one druid dying, and 2 giants up, one of which was the one we wanted. So I took the other one and proceeded to drag him over to the dwarves... which is a good distance away. Had they killed the giant with the leggings while I was out of range for experience, we'd have seen the dreaded trivial msg.  Now, was the fight trivial? Not at all... it tooks us close to half an hour to finish it, because of numerous difficulties.  Yet, out of range would result in a trivial fight?<br>
<br>
How does this make sense... another example.<br>
Dreadlands is a nice and big zone.  Have a group out at the back of karnor's, killing things. Let's say the leader of the group is a druid and gates out to pick someone up, then brings them back. So you have 4 folks out on one side of karnors, 2 others at the druid circle.  Let's say some high level mob shows up (dont think dreadlands has many named, but there are a few) and the 4 folks at karnor's kill it while the other 2 are still at circle. POOF.  Regardless of levels involved. .it simply goes poof.<br>
<br>
TLC code is programmed to react simply on &quot;If anyone in the group gets no experience&quot;<br>
<br>
It should be modified to say..<br>
<br>
&quot;If anyone in the group gets no experience, and it's not because the highest level member and the lowest level member are too far apart to gain experience together.&quot;<br>
<br>
and<br>
&quot;If anyone in the group gets no experience, and it's not because anyone is out of range physically.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, it's more complicated to program.. but it would make TLC make a lot more sense.<br>
